name: VCF Operations
author: Broadcom, Inc.
info:
The VMware Cloud Foundation Operations content pack is provided to present log data in a more meaningful way and to analyze all the logs redirected from VMware Cloud Foundation Operations instance(s). The content pack contains various dashboards, queries and alerts to provide better diagnostics and troubleshooting capabilities to the VMware Cloud Foundation Operations (aka. VCF Operations) administrator. The content pack provides: 

 Proactive monitoring and alert notifications of the VCF Operations cluster(s): Specific alerts focused on important events that indicate problems can be enabled to get the alerts in VCF Operations as well as for sending emails to the administrator(s).
 Cluster-role specific breakdown of VCF Operations events: The dashboards can be filtered according to the cluster role of the VCF Operations nodes/slices like Master, Data, Replica and Remote Collector to provide better manageability.

 Highlights: The VCF Operations content pack provides a consolidated summary of log events across all VCF Operations components of the environment including the Operations Telemetry, Operations casa components, Gemfire, Analytics, Collectors. This version of the content pack is designed specifically for VCF Operations (previously vROps) 9.0 or above.
    - Proactive monitoring of VCF Operations environment
    - Component-specific breakdown of VCF Operations events
    - Troubleshooting and root-cause analysis.

 Compatibility: The VCF Operations content pack is designed for VCF Operations for Logs (previously vRLI) version 9.0+ and VCF Operations (previously vROps) version 9.0+, but majority of the components stays still compatible for old configured environments of versions.

IMPORTANT: Starting from 6.7 version of VCF Operations (previously vROps), the only recommended way to configure log forwarding is through Administration > Management > Log Forwarding.
For older versions of VCF Operations the manual VCF Operations for Logs Agent configuration is still expected to be done. For directions on proper agent configuration see the Setup Instructions of the Content Pack.
instructions:
Configuring the VMware Cloud Foundation Operations for Logs (aka. VCF Operations for Logs) Agent

The VCF Operations for Logs Agent enables the integration and manages communication between VCF Operations for Logs and VCF Operations.

IMPORTANT: Starting from 6.7 version of VCF Operations (previously vROps), configuration is simplified. Now, the only recommended way to configure log forwarding is through Administration > Management > Log Forwarding. No additional manual configuration for liagent.ini file is expected as it was advised earlier. All the below mentioned tags are being automatically configured from VCF Operations.
 
Any previously defined agent configuration should be removed before enabling Log Forwarding to ensure that no duplicate events get delivered to VCF Operations for Logs.

alerts.name: VC stats query time-out occurred
alerts.info: The purpose of this alert is to notify when the VCF Operations instance is not able to get the data back from vCenter instance within the 5 minute interval and the metrics back up and get dropped with the error: Communication Error:  com.integrien.adapter.vmware.VcCollector.collectMetrics - Vc stats query timed out (ms): 300377. This is usually due to intermittent connection issues with the vCenter and hosts or down to the network not able to handle the request and timing out.

alerts.name: xDB Xhive exception messages
alerts.info: XhiveException is the base exception used throughout all of xDB. It is thrown when some database operation did not complete in the normal way. Such exceptions might stem from fatal conditions or recoverable problems and would need more analysis to root cause the real issue.

alerts.name: Analytics Service Start/Restart
alerts.info: This alert gets generated when the Analytics Service gets started or restarted. It checks for the service [WrapperListener_start_runner] com.integrien.analytics.AnalyticsMain.start and captures its start/restart. As Analytics service is the main component of the VCF Operations system, very frequent start/stop and restart of the service might indicate that the system is becoming unstable.

alerts.name: SSL Handshake exception occurred
alerts.info:
The purpose of this alert is to notify when importing data into VCF Operations 6.0 from VCF Operations 5.8.x fails with the error: Communication Error: Timeout reached while trying to communicate with the server. Try refreshing the UI manually (2100944).

For more information, refer to the KB - http://kb.vmware.com/kb/2100944

widgets.name: Dashboards activity
widgets.info:
The widget shows all actions triggered from "Dashboards" menu related to  Dashboards, Views and Reports.

Note: This includes admin and internal users.

widgets.name: Alerts activity
widgets.info:
The widget shows all actions triggered from "Alerts" menu related to Alert definition and Symptom definition.

Note: This includes admin and internal users.

widgets.name: Environment activity
widgets.info:
The widget shows all actions triggered from "Environment" menu related to  Custom Groups and Custom Datacenters.

Note: This includes admin and internal users.

widgets.name: User management activity
widgets.info:
The widget shows all actions triggered from "Administration" menu related to Users, User Groups and Roles.

Note: This includes admin and internal users.

widgets.name: Configuration activity
widgets.info:
The widget shows all actions triggered from "Administration" menu related to  Policies, Super Metrics, Collector Groups, Disk Re-balance, Global Settings, Dynamic Threshold and Describe.

Note: This includes admin and internal users.

widgets.name: Inventory activity
widgets.info:
The widget lists all changes to the Objects in the Inventory. It lists all actions triggered from objects' detail pages, the Inventory or Alerts also.

Note: This includes admin and internal users.

widgets.info:

Please note that this widget reflect actions performed by all users including admin.
